        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>6. Q. A. St.</placeName>
                    <date>Tuesday Evening</date>
                    <salute>My dear Lyell</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I will call tomorrow morning a little after 9. in hopes of seeing you.—</p>
<p>You will understand if I do not appear that I am not very well.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Ever yours | Ch. Darwin</p>
<p>I return with thanks the Saturday R<hi rend="superscript">w</hi>.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> The Coral-Reef Book has been invaluable to me.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9231.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 8 January 1874</ref>, and by CD’s stay in London from 10 to 17 January 1874 (see ‘Journal’ (Appendix II)). During CD’s visit, Tuesday fell on 13 January 1874.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">According to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin’s</ref> diary (DAR 242), CD fell down the stairs on Monday 12 January 1874.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><hi rend="italic">Saturday Review</hi> was published weekly; it is not certain which issue CD borrowed.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD was preparing a second edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1571.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Coral reefs</hi></ref>. In a <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9231.xml" resp="#automat" cert="medium">letter to Joseph Dalton Hooker of 8 January 1874</ref>, he had asked to use a copy of the book for corrections. CD evidently used Lyell’s copy instead.</note>
        </div>        
            
